<K6 id="示例输出" load="on_request">
示例文章骨架 | Example Article Skeleton (topic A1: soft_splice_blind_spot)

TITLE: Why Metal Conveyor Splices Compromise Food Line Metal Detection

P1_HOOK: In food processing plants running conveyor-fed metal detection, the splice holding the belt together can be the source of the contamination event the detector was installed to prevent. Standard metal alligator lacing passes through the detector field once per belt revolution, forcing the system to blank its sensitivity window to ignore the known metal source. That window — typically 150 to 250 milliseconds — is a detection gap that repeats every cycle, at every production rate, for the life of the belt.

P2_MECHANISM: Metal detectors operate by measuring field disturbance from conductive materials passing through the aperture. When metal lacing passes through, the system cannot distinguish splice from contaminant. Manufacturers address this with secondary sensors that detect the splice position and trigger a timed blank — effectively turning off detection for a fraction of a second. That fraction compounds: on a 200-foot-per-minute line running 20 hours, the cumulative undetected window exceeds 90 seconds per shift. Any ferrous fragment timed with the splice passes through undetected.

P3_CONTRAST: Standard industry practice accepts metal lacing as a functional compromise. Conveyor manufacturers specify lacing rated for their belt load and focus on splice strength, not detection continuity. The blank-and-compensate approach is widely accepted by equipment integrators as a solved problem. It is not. It transfers contamination liability to the detection gap, not the detector.

P4_GUIDANCE: Bunting partnered with Belt Services to develop a non-metallic soft splice using fiberglass or plastic pins rated for the same tensile loads as metal alligator lacing. The splice passes through the detector aperture without triggering a blank. Detection runs continuously through the full belt revolution. For facilities under USDA, FDA 21 CFR, or FSMA Preventive Controls jurisdiction, continuous detection without a programmed blank is the only defensible design in a metal control CCP.

P5_FIELD_TIPS: Specify soft splices at installation, not retrofit. Field-replacing metal lacing on a running production line requires full belt removal and often shortens belt life at the new splice point. When evaluating conveyor packages that include metal detection, ask the integrator for the splice spec and the blank duration spec as separate line items. If the integrator cannot provide both, the detection system is incomplete.

